</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>SJR16:v99#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="SJR16"/><meta name="dc:title" content="SJR &#xA;              16-&#xA;                INTRODUCED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Joint Resolution
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 16</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Caballero<br/>(Coauthors: Senators Arreguín and Cortese)<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>May 07, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> Relative to vehicles. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SJR 16, as introduced, Caballero.
                          Vehicles: commercial driver’s license revocation.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This measure would urge the Congress of the United States and the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration to review federal commercial driver’s license disqualification policies and consider reforms that allow greater flexibility for states and appropriate relief for drivers whose livelihoods are affected.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><span class="Resolution" title="source: /caml:MeasureDoc/caml:Resolution&#xA;    "><span class="Whereas" id="id_7F5B0265-6FB7-4D89-9D79-E112E77CC42D"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Commercial drivers play a necessary role in the movement of essential goods, and are an integral part of California’s economy; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_6812B372-3D2C-4C36-AB82-319319F63D62"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, There are over 700,000 commercial drivers in California; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_92B65951-2E9A-47F5-A51F-C05C8AF3F114"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Commercial drivers transport essential medicine, food, and necessary fuels that people rely on every day; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_024AE4BA-7B5F-4670-9EB7-29A547FB974B"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, California relies on commercial drivers to transport shipping containers from its 12 seaports and that traffic is approximately 40 percent of imported shipping container traffic across the United States; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_BF3F9171-89D0-417A-9045-68EAD6E99BFA"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Commercial drivers do this job for weeks on end, to facilitate the efficient logistical operation of everyday business, without seeing their families; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_A36C888C-44B6-4095-A6CE-26D291F8DE57"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Federal regulations governing commercial driver’s licenses are administered by the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_15A88224-5348-4A7D-AEF5-02AA4947DBCE"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Revised federal disqualification rules have resulted in the suspension or permanent loss of an estimated 17,000 commercial driver’s licenses, effectively ending a driver’s ability to earn a livelihood; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_CF1A29DD-831D-4204-A947-3D2006442956"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, These disqualifications occurred even in cases where the underlying conduct did not involve unsafe operation of a commercial motor vehicle; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_1FBEEFB6-8C80-4FDD-B677-206040897DCE"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The trucking industry continues to experience workforce shortages that affect supply chains and economic stability; now, therefore, be it</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_67E70697-2851-4DA9-8D7E-2C280815E80C"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved by the Senate and the Assembly of the State of California, jointly, That the Legislature respectfully urges the Congress of the United States and the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration to review federal commercial driver’s license disqualification policies and consider reforms that allow greater flexibility for states and appropriate relief for drivers whose livelihoods are affected; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_C6A3B059-AB41-431F-A9A1-7278F8212748"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Secretary of the Senate transmit copies of this resolution to the President of the United States, the Administrator of the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration, to each Member of the California delegation in the Congress of the United States, and to the author for appropriate distribution.</div></span></span></div></body></html>
